			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Azrael : some fluffing is usefull / important for game balance, I agree.
<br />

<br />
What people don't like is Abusive fluffing which gives advantages to certain players but not others, namely those in the dominant council or its allies. It is too easy for the top council to dominate the rest and abusive fluffing is one of the reasons. An abusive fluffer sits on a very high score out of the range of anyone else, knowing that no-one can hit him, or even fluff up to a high enough score to hit him without hours of gunboat building. But doing so puts the player trying to catch up in serious danger of getting killed by the dominant council.
<br />

<br />
Fluff should be a risky tactic.. worthwhile to hide your real power but carrying a risk of getting caught and raped. Anyone not in a dominant council who logs off while fluffed ALWAYS runs a serious risk of dying, 'cos he can get warred by people much stronger than his real power and 'cos his score won't drop much 'cos of his fluff so he can lose ALL his planets to them.
<br />

<br />
This risk is simply not there for the serious (abusive fluffers) who fluff up above everyone else's score. For the sakes of fair gameplay, an advantage which is ONLY available to the TOP is NOT REASONABLE. Gamebalance demands that either everyone has the same options, or that extra options are available only at the bottom (to help catching up)</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
